Modeling and prediction for movies

Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(statsr)
library(GGally)

Load data

load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

The data set was collected through randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016. It is generalizable to all the movies generated and released before 2016 because of the random sampling method used and a large sample collected. However, it may not be generalizable to movies produced afterwards, since the movie industry may have changed and evolved. It is an observational experiment overall and no random assignment was used, thus no causality can be drawn.

Part 2: Research question

What are the factors associated with the popularity of a movie produced and released before 2016?

Figuring out the factors that may be associated with the popularity of a movie could be the utmost wonder of a movie producer. It is also informative to know for a member of the audience as it could be helpful to write a contributive review of a movie.

Part 4: Modeling

1. Specify which variables to consider for the full model

The variables considered are title_type, genre, runtime, thtr_rel_year, imdb_rating, thtr_rel_month, thtr_rel_day, dvd_rel_year, dvd_rel_month, dvd_rel_day, best_pic_nom, best_pic_win, best_actor_win, best_actress_win, best_dir_win and top200_box for the full model.

2. Reasoning for excluding certain variables

Some variables are irrelevant for the analysis such as the rt_url and imdb_url. Others like audience_rating, critics_score, and so on are not independent, and show collinearity. Actors are also excluded because they are less contributive to a statistical analysis like this.

3. Reasoning for choice of model selection method

The reason for choosing a three-factor model is because it has highest adjusted R value compared to previous ones. There is no big increase in the R value from two factor to three factor. Whether it is the parsimonious model will need further investigations.

4. Carrying out the model selection correctly

The analysis starts from forward selection for linear regression. Adjusted R-square is used to determine if the variable is significant and thus be included in the final linear model. The overall correlation coefficient is 0.762044.The detailed analysis is illustrated in EDA.

5. Model diagnostics

Linearity & Constant Variability

ggplot(data = m34, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
  xlab("Fitted values") +
  ylab("Residuals")

The plot shows that the data is clustered from x = 50 to x = 75 region. The residuals are much larger for the data in this region. The constant variability test for this model failed.

Nearly Normal Residuals

ggplot(data = m34, aes(x = .resid)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10) +
  xlab("Residuals")

The residuals do show a nearly normal distribution centered at zero, and fairly symmetric, as shown in the plot above.

Normal Probability Plot

ggplot(data = m34, aes(sample = .resid)) +
  stat_qq()

The line in the above plot does not suggest any time-series related date. There is no particular pattern in the residual as order increases.

From the summary statistics, we can see that the relationship between audience_score and imdb_rating is positive, an increase of one point in imdb_rating is associated with 16.1032 increase in audience_score. The p-value is extremely small suggesting the statistics significance of the estimate. The genre variable is less clear in that different genre do show different relationships with audience_score, some increase and other decrease. The p-values are less significant - the two show significance are Animation and Mystery & Suspense. Besides, the release month is negatively associated with audience_score as reflected in the negative of the slope. The overall model indicates an increase in adjusted R squared value when thtr_rel_month is factored in, although the p-value for t-statistics is only 6.12%. * * *

Part 5: Prediction

DrivingMissDaisy <- data.frame(genre = "Drama", imdb_rating = 7.4, thtr_rel_month = 6, audience_score = 81)
DMD <- round(predict(m34, DrivingMissDaisy), digit = 0)
c(DMD, DrivingMissDaisy$audience_score)
##  1    
## 77 81

The predicted value is less than the actual audience_score, showing a negative residual.

predict(m34, DrivingMissDaisy, interval = 'prediction', level = 0.95)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 77.23024 57.81705 96.64344

We are 95% confident that the audience_score of Driving Miss Daisy is in the range of 57.81705 to 96.64344.

Part 6: Conclusion

After layers of analyses, we came to the realization that imdb_rating is highly associated with the audience_score. Other factors that increase the R-squared value are thtr_rel_month and genre but with less significance and with both negative and positive associations in their sub-categories. The audience_score is chosen as the response variable, if other variables such as critics_score or imdb_num_votes, the model may be different compared to the one illustrated in this analysis.
